  "amb_1994_10_312":  {
                          "subject":  "Rumours about Enigma",
                          "from":  "Gavin Stok \u003cgpsto1@aurora.cc.monash.edu.au\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Sat, 22 Oct 1994 18:26:02 +1000 (EST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eG\u0027day. Jon wrote:\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003e The book with Trance Europe Express 2 had an interesting little story on \u003cbr\u003e\u003e Enigma. Apparently their \u0027Out of the Deep\u0027 track is a reworking of APL\u0027s \u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u0027The Calling\u0027. Large sums of money were paid to APL which was expected to \u003cbr\u003e\u003e pay for their studio. IMO Enigma are typical of the predatory major label \u003cbr\u003e\u003e attitude to developing styles of music.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  Seems like Trance Europe Express 2 should check their information. I haveheard both tracks and the only similarity is that the Enigma track has a samplefrom APL. All this junk about commercialism and the \u0026#34;big bad record companies\u0026#34;seems very hard to swallow by me, especially since Michael Cretu (the man whois Enigma) had 3 years before he released a new studio album.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  Don\u0027t always believe what you read people!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eGavin Stok\u003cbr\u003e(Enigma Mailing List President)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003egps@yoyo.cc.monash.edu.au\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_231":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: 99% have no chance",
                          "from":  "drm%mssls3.mssl.ucl.ac.uk@ucl.ac.uk (David Mantripp)",
                          "dateString":  "Tue, 18 Oct 94 15:53:34 BST",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003e I think both are missing the point. High-quality recording and \u003cbr\u003e\u003e reproduction is much more important to electronic music (of almost any \u003cbr\u003e\u003e genre) than music based on acoustic instruments. When you listen to a \u003cbr\u003e\u003e recording of a saxophonist, it doesn\u0027t matter if the recording is perfect \u003cbr\u003e\u003e or not, because you recognise the instrument and your brain fills in the \u003cbr\u003e\u003e gaps to rebuild the sound image.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eCome on!!! Do you _know_ any saxophonists ? Do you really think that\u003cbr\u003ethey all sound exactly the same ?  The sometimes tiny nuances that are\u003cbr\u003eonly reproduced on quality equipment are vitally important to define\u003cbr\u003ean individual\u0027s style.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHowever, that point is just to refute any discrimination between acousticand electronic instruments.  I\u0027d say that the acoustic if anything are\u003cbr\u003emore important.  As for hi-fi, well the average maniac who has gone out\u003cbr\u003eand bought the top flight gold plated mega system would be quite horrifiedto see the sort of connections the music went through at source....\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe thing is that the musician looses control of the music once it has\u003cbr\u003ebeen recorded.  This debate about equipment doesn\u0027t even consider the\u003cbr\u003edifferences between the essential item of equipment we all use - our\u003cbr\u003eears.  Who can say if a particular sound is the same for person A and\u003cbr\u003eperson B ? The whole thing is irretrievably subjective, as is describingmusic with words. There is as much interaction between the listener and\u003cbr\u003ethe music as there is between the musician and the music, and my feelingis that the mark of a really succesful musician is the knack of being\u003cbr\u003eable to include enough possibilities with the parameters of the compositionto stimulate the listener into becoming a part of the process. One \u003cbr\u003eoustanding example of someone who succeeds in this is Eno.  Music X on\u003cbr\u003ea $200 system is not worse than on a $20000, just different, and (probably)further away from the sound in the studio. But one thing is certain -\u003cbr\u003enobody will _ever_ hear it exactly as the musician heard it at the time\u003cbr\u003eit was recorded, and it\u0027s futile to try.\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_462":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: The dark side of ... ...",
                          "from":  "XdadaX@aol.com",
                          "dateString":  "Sun, 30 Oct 1994 03:08:40 -0500",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003eSo, the moral of this somewhat directionless tirade is that there\u0027s \u003emoreto ambient than Tangerine Dream, FAX, Harold Budd\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eVery true...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e. I, for one,\u003cbr\u003eam going to make a point of picking up some of these non-mainstream\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;ambient\u0026#34; releases, because it\u0027s good for me, has plenty of vitamins, andwon\u0027t cause this list to become totally \u0026#34;Artificial\u0026#34; like the IDM list.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf FAX considered \u0026#34;mainstream\u0026#34; now? Most people I mention FAX too still havenever heard of the label and there are even some people on this mailing listwho don\u0027t know who Namlook is!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTony\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eon now:  Coil - Nasa-arab 12\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
