  "amb_1994_09_17":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: labels-n-such",
                         "from":  "will@panix.com (WILL-E)",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 13 Sep 1994 01:04:08 -0400",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003eIn his posting, Robert quoted Delerium\u0027s After 6am label as qualifying\u003cbr\u003e\u003eas ambient, but the only one of those records that I have (Solar Eclipse)\u003cbr\u003e\u003eI would have given as trance, so I was wondering where ambient really\u003cbr\u003e\u003ebegins, and consequently where this list stops?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eregarding the after 6am label, a number of the records are indeed beatlessambience and quite nice too.  Then again, you have to consider that after6am is the ambient sublabel for Delirium which is a hardcore/hardtrance\u003cbr\u003elabel out of Germany.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI imagine that because ambient is such an intentionally vague name \u0026\u003cbr\u003emusical genre, that the direction of this list will generate some openessto varied ideas on what ambient can be.  Hopefully we can just enjoy whatit means to each of us through the music and not by attempting to nail adefinition on it.  Often I find that to define something is also to destroyit.  What I\u0027m trying to say is that I don\u0027t want to argue about what is orisn\u0027t ambient but focusing instead on what it is that we enjoy about it.Does this make sense?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e                      ___\u003cbr\u003e / /  /  /  /   /  _  __/\u003cbr\u003e(_/__/  /  (__ (__  ___/\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
