  "amb_1994_09_51":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: opinions of instinct discs....",
                         "from":  "Matt Corwine \u003cmcorwine@u.washington.edu\u003e",
                         "dateString":  "Mon, 19 Sep 1994 09:53:19 -0700 (PDT)",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOn Mon, 19 Sep 1994 Number19@aol.com wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e the one ambient disk release from Instinct that I own is one of those\u003cbr\u003e\u003e licensed jobbies, this one from em:t, the ambient subsid of t:me. I love all\u003cbr\u003e\u003e the progressive house coming out on t:me, so I was real happy to see Instinct\u003cbr\u003e\u003e pick this one up -- more of an urban/world-style ambient tip (not very\u003cbr\u003e\u003e space/drone, or experimental, a la the Exursions in Ambience series). Emit is INCREDIBLE.  Check out some of the import CD-only releases on \u003cbr\u003ethat label, which I judge to be the best, most creative listening music around.  Woob and Qubism in particular are incredible.  Thought-out, \u003cbr\u003ewell-executed, rich music.  Buy it all and buy it now :-)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePeace,\u003cbr\u003e::Matthew J. Corwine                         Online Editor, XLR8R Magazine::::mcorwine@hyperreal.com                               xlr8r@hyperreal.com::::mcorwine@u.washington.edu                  Ambient Temple of Imagination::::206.328.9368                                          atoi@hyperreal.com::\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
