  "amb_1994_09_119":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: FSOL interview",
                          "from":  "rbcIII \u003crobot@svpal.org\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 23 Sep 1994 16:02:21 -0700 (PDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYou know I really like FSOL and RDJ but there\u0027s already a list practically dedicated to them (and Orbital) called IDM.  In fact they talk about them so much over there that they should rename the list Richard\u0027s Future \u003cbr\u003eSound of Orbital or something.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnyway I hope this list doesn\u0027t get over run with talk about RDJ, FSOL and Orbital.  I know they all do borderline ambient work (esp. Mr. James, of course), but I\u0027m sick of hearing about them (as is a lot of other people I know).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis list has gotten off to such a good start.  Let\u0027s not ruin it now.  I hope I\u0027ve not offended anyone, but IDM is such a better place for those three.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e-robert\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_514":  {
                          "subject":  "Carnage Visors",
                          "from":  "vilexile \u003ceinexile@netcom.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Mon, 31 Oct 1994 23:45:36 -0800 (PST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u0027appy \u0027allowe\u0027en! 8O\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOn Mon, 31 Oct 1994, Timothy Edwards wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e Hell, einexile (hello 4ADer) considered a Cure album in his top 10\u003cbr\u003e\u003e ambient list. The Cure isn\u0027t exactly ambient but the album/pieces on that\u003cbr\u003e\u003e particular album may be.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eCarnage Visors as ambient may be pushing it, but it is long and slow and pusating and subdued. I honestly hadn\u0027t listened to it in a long time \u003cbr\u003ewhen I wrote down that to ten list, but I\u0027m listening to it now and I\u0027ll stick by it. It was the soundtrack to an animated film made I think my a friend or sibling of one member of the band, and, having been recorded \u003cbr\u003ebetween Seventeen Seconds and Faith, it flows with that slow cool \u003cbr\u003estrumming that dominated both albums, an ominous, menacing little \u003cbr\u003ebassline, and a scary, thumpy drum pattern. Themes develop and play out, then die down and are later replaced with variations. It\u0027s a pretty \u003cbr\u003eactive record, but a good one to relax with. It\u0027s ambient in the way that the Insides are ambient, perhaps, but certainly less questionable than a lot of the trance that gets measured in here. (No condemnation intended by that as I actually prefer that sort of thing.) Oh, I should mention \u003cbr\u003ethat there is no singing in the song, it is half an hour long, and can be found on the back of the cassette release for Seventeen Seconds. (A \u003cbr\u003emarvelous album indeed. Are The Cure thislisty?)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e einexile falls back in fields of the neroli\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
