  "amb_1994_10_303":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: 4 seconds",
                          "from":  "Jamess \u003cjamess@firefox.co.uk\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 21 Oct 94 12:13:16 +0100 (BST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e My CD player claims that Global Communication\u0027s 76 14 is in fact\u003cbr\u003e\u003e 76 18.  Maybe it\u0027s because I\u0027ve got the special limited edition\u003cbr\u003e\u003e extended version ???\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis happens a lot.\u003cbr\u003eeg.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMoby\u0027s alt.quiet.whatever.mix of \u0026#34;hymn\u0026#34; claimed on the sleeve and \u003cbr\u003eadverts to be 33.33333 minutes (33:20 I suppose), but was actually \u003cbr\u003e33:45 according to my player.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe UK CD5 of The Orb\u0027s Blue Room was labelled as 39:58, but my CD \u003cbr\u003eplayer said it was 40:00\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMany of Namlook\u0027s CDs have different lengths to the prominently \u003cbr\u003edisplayed times on the discs and sleeves.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOK none of these are actually titles, though the Moby one comes \u003cbr\u003eclose as it was sort of part of the mix title. I chose them because \u003cbr\u003ethey are all \u0026#34;ambient\u0026#34;, and the timing is a significant part of the \u003cbr\u003elabelling or concept of the disc.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThere remains the mystery as to why it happens.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJ\u003cbr\u003e^\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNEW. Signature lite (TM). Not interesting to look at but better for the net. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
