  "amb_1994_09_232":  {
                          "subject":  "Re(2): FAX ",
                          "from":  "\"Dana WATANABE\" \u003cDWATANAB@uci.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 30 Sep 94 16:58:36 PDT",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003e I also picked up a recording of a live show Namlook did in San Francisco, and\u003cbr\u003e\u003e found that to be quite incredible as well, and anything but silent. It was\u003cbr\u003e\u003e mostly a continuous percussion track with intermitant breaks of keyboard\u003cbr\u003e\u003e noises. But, instead of just discounting this as mere \u0026#34;swooshy\u0026#34; stuff, it is\u003cbr\u003e\u003e interesting to judge the piece on its dynamics. It ranges from fairly heavy\u003cbr\u003e\u003e percussion, to more quiet, sometimes eerie synthesizer noises and vocals.\u003cbr\u003e\u003e Very droning and cool.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI\u0027m assuming this is Power Supply.  I really like this, but i was\u003cbr\u003eactually at the show and was completely blown away by \u003cbr\u003eNamlook and Morris (who also performed/DJ\u0027d).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOn the disk, the synthesized little \u0026#34;This is San Francisco\u0026#34; thing\u003cbr\u003eis quite cheesey, but i think that the part that is most enveloping\u003cbr\u003e(again cuz it was the same way at teh show)\u003cbr\u003eis when the beat kicks in.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFor months after that show, anytime a similar slow beat kicked in,\u003cbr\u003ei couldnt help but sway around swimming inside of it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e ,\u003cbr\u003edana\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;Do you remember that part of the song, the one with that crackling sound? It\u0027s just Not Right that someone can do that to me.\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_252":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: ambient music and Dolby surround",
                          "from":  "Interstellar Groovy Dave \u003ccamde933@uidaho.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Tue, 18 Oct 1994 16:48:03 -0700 (PDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \tI was wondering why people don\u0027t start to make ambient records in the\u003cbr\u003e\u003e Dolby surround format. I would think the surround sound coding will\u003cbr\u003e\u003e greatly enhance the listening pleasure of ambient music.\u003cbr\u003e\tThat would be fun to use, having things go sailling around while I\u0027m \u003cbr\u003emixing.  Heheheh...Dolby Surround Dave.  8-)  Spooky...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \tMaybe higher cost for surround coding is the concern here, or\u003cbr\u003e\u003e maybe it is the marketing problem with surround format? Any thoughts\u003cbr\u003e\u003e out there?\u003cbr\u003e\tI\u0027m not sure what encoders run, but well out of my price range.  8-)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\t\tGroovy Dave\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e-----------*------------*-----------*-----------*--------------*------------- 0 0    *------------* \t\u003cbr\u003e  |     |Groovy Dave!|  \tcamde933@uidaho.edu\u003cbr\u003e\\___/\t*------------*\tThe Official Groovy Dave Mini-Sig\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
