  "amb_1994_10_46":  {
                         "subject":  "Orb split??",
                         "from":  "transmat@teleport.com",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 11 Oct 1994 10:05:45 -0800",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eThe following is from the UK Dance Digest - for what it is worth - idle\u003cbr\u003egossip or otherwise:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDate: Mon, 10 Oct 1994 15:12:38 +0100 (bst)\u003cbr\u003eFrom: n.pitamber@imperial.ac.uk\u003cbr\u003eSubject: ORB TO HEMI-ORB\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  Just in case any one is interested, The Orb spitt the other day.\u003cbr\u003eApparently Kris (aka Thrash) was fed up with doing all the hard work,\u003cbr\u003eand then Alex P just coming along and putting tacky samples in it.\u003cbr\u003e  Personly, I quite like their use of samples. May be Kris is more of\u003cbr\u003ea purist.\u003cbr\u003e  They may even get back together as they are still friends, but as it\u003cbr\u003estands, there will be one more album, then, seeeyaa!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e            DUB\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ebleep...bleep...transmat@teleport.com\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
  "amb_1994_10_247":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: ambient music and Dolby surround",
                          "from":  "Michael Joly \u003celectric@world.std.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Tue, 18 Oct 1994 17:21:54 +0059 (EDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eI\u0027ve played a few surround encoded DATs on my radio show but I haven\u0027t \u003cbr\u003eseen any commercially available ambient CDs encoded with Dolby Surround. \u003cbr\u003eLin is right that there is an additional expense incurred producing Dolby Surround encoded material - Dolby charges for the use of the matrix \u003cbr\u003eencoder and also charges a fee to have an engineer present at the mix.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBut perhaps the lack of surround sound ambient titles is due to the fact that until recently there hasn\u0027t been a large installed base of Pro-logic equipped home audio system - sort of like when mono lp\u0027s were still being manufactured in the late 60\u0027s because not everyone had \u0026#34;a stereo\u0026#34;.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI recently concluded a 15 year stint designing surround sound \u003cbr\u003eencoders/decoders and theatrical exhibition sound systems and spent quite a few hours listening to 35mm film soundtrack ambiences in commercial and home theatres. I agree with Lin that surround sound, or spatialization, can increase the ambient effect.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIt appears that quite a few CD\u0027s are using some spatialization technology like the Roland RSS, Hughes SRS, Q Sound, B.A.S.E. or binaural mic\u0027ing to enhance that sence of being inside the music. The first four processes \u003cbr\u003esuffer from sweet spot dependency (you have to be right at the apex of an equilateral triangle with the loudspeakers at the base points for best \u003cbr\u003eeffects to be heard.) The binaural mic technique is often accompanied by the dreaded \u0026#34;front/back reversal\u0026#34; - a listener experiences an ambiguous directionality for sounds that originate directly in front of, or in back of the binaural head michrophone.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThere is a technology just around the corner though that will enable \u003cbr\u003erobust spatialization of audio images - the new digital, discrete channel surround processes which will be migrating from the cinema exhibition \u003cbr\u003eworld to the home in the next year or so.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eCurrently, in the cinema there are three principle digital surround \u003cbr\u003esystems - Dolby\u0027s, Sony\u0027s and DTS\u0027s (funded in part by Universal Studios) and all three companies are working on non-compatible consumer versions of their pro products. Here comes VHS vs Beta again...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnyway, once the dust settles I\u0027m sure more producers and lables will be looking to release ambient music recorded in a discrete multichannel \u003cbr\u003edigital format - and create soundscapes with a greater sense of depth \u003cbr\u003ethan current two channel stereo or even matrix surround can offer. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThat just leaves height information missing to create true 3D \u003cbr\u003esoundscapes...perhaps height info can be matrixed onto the discrete \u003cbr\u003elateral info...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIn the meantime, try listening to your ambient tracks thru a surround \u003cbr\u003esound system and if you\u0027re in the Boston area listen to some original \u003cbr\u003esurround sound mixes on \u0026#34;ElectricSpace\u0026#34; - Tues 12:30 to 2:30am on WMBR 88.1\u003cbr\u003eregards\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMichael Joly\u003cbr\u003esoundman mj on \u0026#34;ElectricSpace\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
