  "amb_1994_10_59":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: top ten list",
                         "from":  "Jason Bunston \u003cjbunston@comp.uark.edu\u003e",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 11 Oct 1994 18:49:09 -0500 (CDT)",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\tHey, in light od all the nice lists that everyone has been \u003cbr\u003ethrowing on here, I would like to know if anyone would be interested\u003cbr\u003ein putting all of their Top Ten choices on a couple of tapes and dubbing that to a blank tape I\u0027d be more than eager to send your way. I don\u0027t \u003cbr\u003ehave the time or money resources to look up all the cool sounding tracks everyone has that are harder to find. I have the major compilations from places like Silent, and Astralwerks/Antler-Subway/Barramundi, etc. But as for the really good obscure stuff I just don\u0027t have the sources. If \u003cbr\u003eanyone would be willing to do a short taping I\u0027d be incredibly \u003cbr\u003egrateful--or better yet if there is something you are looking for that I might have we could do a trade. Thanks in advance!!\u003cbr\u003e\t\u003cbr\u003e\t\tJ.B. in way-out-of-the-way-Fayetteville Arkansas.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
  "amb_1994_10_262":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Namlook / Aphex",
                          "from":  "\"Ken Stuart\" \u003cken@snowcrest.net\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Tue, 18 Oct 94 22:59:50 PDT",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eOn Tue, 18 Oct 94 10:57:45 +0100 (BST), \u003cbr\u003eJamess  \u003cjamess@firefox.co.uk\u003e wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eIn the booklet accompanying Trance-Europe-Express Vol 2, there was \u003cbr\u003e\u003ean article/interview about/with Pete Namlook (written by Mixmaster \u003cbr\u003e\u003eMorris), in which it was suggested that he was about to embark on a \u003cbr\u003e\u003ejoint project with Richard James. Has anyone heard anything further \u003cbr\u003e\u003eabout this? It\u0027s just that a record which combined elements of AWII \u003cbr\u003e\u003eand (for instance) \u0026#34;Air\u0026#34; would have a hard time not being pretty \u003cbr\u003e\u003eincredible, right?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI think that logic says so, but reality doesn\u0027t.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWhen I heard that the Robert Fripp and the Orb were releasing a joint \u003cbr\u003ealbum, I assumed it would be better than any of their separate ones, but it did not turn out that way -- although it is a fine album (\u0026#34;FFWD\u003e\u003e\u0026#34;).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI thought about it subsequently and I think it comes down to that artists that are self-sufficient don\u0027t gain or pick up anything from being with other equal self-sufficient artists.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFor example, when Genesis broke up into Peter Gabriel, Steve Hackett, and the \u0026#34;other 3\u0026#34; :-) , each artist/group seemed to be missing the \u003cbr\u003echaracteristics previously provided by the others, and hence (IMHO) was much less artistically successful (although often commercially successful).\u003cbr\u003eI don\u0027t think that Richard James is missing some characteristic of \u003cbr\u003eNamlook, or vice versa.  But they might make a good album, nonetheless.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e-\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003erespect to all,\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eKen            ken@snowcrest.net   (primary address)\u003cbr\u003e               (if no answer, try ken.stuart@tigerteam.org )\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_09_73":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: Fishology",
                         "from":  "will@panix.com (WILL-E)",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 20 Sep 1994 17:09:56 -0400",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003eI quite liked it - does anyone know what album it is off, and whether Dream\u003cbr\u003e\u003eFish have produced anything else?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDreamfish is Pete Namlook and Mixmaster Morris.  It was released initially on FAX records which is Namlook\u0027s label.  Check out my discography for this label at hyperreal.com  in the /labels directory.  It was later reissued by Rising High Records which is the label that Morris is on (usually using the name The Irresistable Force) and a couple of Dreamfish tracks appeared on a number of compilations including The Secret Life of Trance II on Rising High.  There\u0027s only one Dreamfish album so far but I hear there are plans for a second one slated for release either late this year or early next year.   \u003cbr\u003e                       ___\u003cbr\u003e  / /  /  /  /   /  _  __/\u003cbr\u003e (_/__/  /  (__ (__  ___/\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
  "amb_1994_11_268":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Influences of Stapleton/Jackman on r",
                          "from":  "AMBIENCE@delphi.com",
                          "dateString":  "Sun, 27 Nov 1994 23:41:06 -0500 (EST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003eIs anyone becoming aware of the growing influence of \u0026#34;tone-scape\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003erecordings such as NWW\u0027s _Soliloquy for Lilith_ or some of the early\u003cbr\u003eJackman/Organum material in pushing what can be done with ambient music farbeyond the soundscape/concrete approach of Stockhausen (possibly into\u003cbr\u003esomething more along the lines of what Eno envisioned) What I\u0027m talking\u003cbr\u003eabout is the assemblage of pure tones, metallic textures and the like tocreate the illusion of infinite space, arranged in quasiperiodic movementsto suggest an infinite time scale.\u003c\u003c\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  I would point to Nocturnal Emissions too, especially with _Stoneface_,Zoviet France, and even Kit Watkins. The metallic textures make the musicinteresting.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  Who would you point to as the originator of this approach? Dockstader\u003cbr\u003emaybe? I\u0027m not up on the music of Stockhausen.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNP: \u0026#34;Blanche\u0026#34; - Klaus Schulze\u003cbr\u003e____________________________________________________________________________Paul Rafanello                                           ambience@delphi.com____________________________________________________________________________"
                      },
  "amb_1994_09_216":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Global Communication",
                          "from":  "BIGGERSTAFF THAD LEWIS \u003cthad@falcon.cc.ukans.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 30 Sep 1994 13:10:32 -0500 (CDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eOn Thu, 15 Sep 1994, Tamara Palmer wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e *************************************************************************\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \tGlobal Communication transmits a blend of organic and \u003cbr\u003e\u003e industrial ambience from Somerset, England, where they, Tom \u003cbr\u003e\u003e Middleton and Mark Pritchard, keep busy with a multitude of other \u003cbr\u003e\u003e projects as well.  Running their own independent label, Evolution \u003cbr\u003e\u003e Records, and recording other works under the guises of Reload, \u003cbr\u003e\u003e Rebus, and E621 keep their creativity flowing in the numerous \u003cbr\u003e\u003e musical directions they wish to explore.  Like the name of the label \u003cbr\u003e\u003e suggests, Mark and Tom  continually reinvent the concept of sound, \u003cbr\u003e\u003e through deconstruction and rebuilding of elements both natural and \u003cbr\u003e\u003e synthetic.  I spoke with Tom via telephone from a rest point during \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDoes anyone out there know/have any idea what sort of equipment Global \u003cbr\u003eCommunication uses to craft their work (computer, software, synths, etc...)For that matter, how about Black Dog?  Seefeel?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eCurious-\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e-thad\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
