  "amb_1994_11_125":  {
                          "subject":  "CJB (was: RAVERS\u0027 INTERNET etc.)",
                          "from":  "Jeffrey Kihn \u003cjeffkihn@ocf.Berkeley.EDU\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Thu, 17 Nov 1994 01:25:34 -0800",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\\\u003cbr\u003eOK, wait a sec. I\u0027m a little confused. Help me out here.\u003cbr\u003eLet me see if I got this straight.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e1\u003e The CJB passed. True? If so, I\u0027m rather upset about it and will gladly   protest by any effective means. If not, what are they so upset about?\u003cbr\u003e2\u003e The passing of the CJB in the UK implies that the US might pass a\u003cbr\u003e   similar law. Is this what the post suggests? It seems a little\u003cbr\u003e   farfetched, but I wouldn\u0027t count it out. Hey, if 187 can pass....\u003cbr\u003e   (Californians only. No need for flames...I claim political ignorance.)   But presumably they wouldn\u0027t expect to be winning any popularity contests   by passing such an act. The CJB et al are definitely government-agenda...   no PR factors at all...so I doubt preventative complaining will have\u003cbr\u003e   much of an impact.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e3\u003e The passing of the CJB in the UK implies the passing of a similar law   that would apply to \u0026#34;Internet gatherings\u0026#34;. The post pretty clearly\u003cbr\u003e   suggests this, and I\u0027ll side with the flamers on this one.\u003cbr\u003e   Seeing as the Internet owes its existance in the US to the Defense\u003cbr\u003e   Department, the government would be shooting itself in the foot by\u003cbr\u003e   universally limiting access. Selectively limiting access would be\u003cbr\u003e   pretty serious, though you\u0027d have to get pretty low down in the system   to do that. But I also claim ignorance of Internet mechanics.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf anyone can clear this up for me, that would be great. Private mail\u003cbr\u003ewould be fine, assuming everyone\u0027s tired of this.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e--Jeff\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
