  "amb_1994_09_59":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: Interstellar Groovy Dave: Hi There!",
                         "from":  "Mad Gil \u003ccyberpun@wam.umd.edu\u003e",
                         "dateString":  "Mon, 19 Sep 1994 19:17:10 -0400 (EDT)",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eOn Fri, 16 Sep 1994, Andrew Thomas wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003e \tThis idea appeals to me, and because of my time slot, would be \u003cbr\u003e\u003e rather ideal for the early morning hours.  Perhaps from 1am till 2am or \u003cbr\u003e\u003e something like that.  Ambient music is difficult to transmit over the \u003cbr\u003e\u003e airwaves because of the many quiet sounds, and odd little transients, \u003cbr\u003e\u003e especially in the lower registers.  These seem to mess with the \u003cbr\u003e\u003e transmissions slightly, so I\u0027m not sure how \u0026#34;ambient\u0026#34; (as in, background \u003cbr\u003e\u003e noise kind of things) I could go, but am willing to try.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI play a lot of ambient on my show (usually about 2 hours a show), and \u003cbr\u003ebasically, you have to raise the levels so they are still around 0 db.  The problem comes when you get some sound without warning that\u0027s very \u003cbr\u003eloud (FSoL wins the award for that:).  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThere are fa few things you can do.   I usually just pot up the volume so that it\u0027s line at -10db and then when a transient comes, it might peg the needle, but it\u0027s not clipping.  so it\u0027s not the worst thing for your \u003cbr\u003elisteners to hear.\u003cbr\u003eThe other thing is convince whoever holds the money at your station to \u003cbr\u003ebuy a Leveler/compressor.  This is a piece of equipment that will bring up the levels slowly, but the brain really won\u0027t be able to tell, plus \u003cbr\u003ewhen you get a transient, it is automatically negotiated.\u003cbr\u003eAphex makes a very nice piece... :)\u003cbr\u003e\t\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eGil Yaker\t\t\t\t\u003cbr\u003ecyberpun@wam.umd.edu\u003cbr\u003eChief Engineer, WMUC Radio\u003cbr\u003eAM 650 kHz / FM 88.1 MHz \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
