  "amb_1994_10_412":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: another laswell label subharmonic",
                          "from":  "jeff@hybrid.com (Jeff Spirer)",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 28 Oct 94 09:03:11 PDT",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eRobert Horton spoke thusly:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003ewell i picked up Chaos Face on laswell\u0027s subharmonic label. is it\u003cbr\u003e\u003eambient, well a couple of pieces are. some are walls of sound that pound\u003cbr\u003e\u003eyou up against the wall. its great but not easy listening. the ambinet\u003cbr\u003e\u003epieces i\u0027m taping onto one tape the others onto another as they are\u003cbr\u003e\u003ereally different moods, you could say. the music seems to be made by\u003cbr\u003e\u003elaswell and robert musso.\u003cbr\u003e\u003eanyone else heard it?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYes.  Laswell did almost everything on it, although some of it is culledfrom samples from his archives and some of it is samples of non-music\u003cbr\u003esources.  There are vocals by Shin Terei (who is Laswell\u0027s \u0026#34;guide\u0026#34; in\u003cbr\u003eJapan) and Mick Harris (Napalm Death, Scorn, PainKiller).  It is not\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;ambient\u0026#34; but very much \u0026#34;techno\u0026#34; if you want to stick labels on it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJeff\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_11_151":  {
                          "subject":  "Suns of Arqa",
                          "from":  "robot@crl.com",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 18 Nov 1994 23:07:35 -0800 (PST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWow.  Both the ambient and the orb lists mentioned Suns of Arqa in the \u003cbr\u003esame week!  I thought that no-one would ever discover them!  I have \u003cbr\u003eAlap-Joe-Jhala and Arqaology.  This list is from the inside sleeve of Alap:\u003cbr\u003ealbums:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eRevenge if the Mozabites\u003cbr\u003eWadada Magic\u003cbr\u003eIndia?\u003cbr\u003eLive with Prince Far-I\u003cbr\u003eArk of the Arquans\u003cbr\u003eWhite Band Speak With Forked Tongue\u003cbr\u003eSeven\u003cbr\u003eJaggernaut (Arka 2103)\u003cbr\u003eLand of a 1,000 Churches (Arka 2101)\u003cbr\u003eCradle\u003cbr\u003eAlap-Joe-Jhala (Arka 2102)\u003cbr\u003eKoromochi (Arka 2104)\u003cbr\u003eArquaology (Arka 2105)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eother Arka Sound releases:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eLone Star and the Sprout Head Uprising (AS 5032)\u003cbr\u003eLone Star - Songs of Jesus (Arka 2106)\u003cbr\u003eMelodies of the master Beinsa Douno (Arka 2107)\u003cbr\u003eThe Earthling - Live (Arka 2108)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eyou can reach Arka Sound at:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e23 Whitechapel Street\u003cbr\u003eManchester M20 OUB\u003cbr\u003eEngland\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003efax: 061-339 3013\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI\u0027m sure there are newer releases since I bought these over a year ago.  I think that most (who like ambient) would enjoy the Sun\u0027s mixture of \u003cbr\u003ebeats and Sitar.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e-robert\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_377":  {
                          "subject":  "ambientext: din",
                          "from":  "terremt@mail.med.cornell.edu (Terre Thaemlitz)",
                          "dateString":  "Thu, 27 Oct 1994 15:52:42 -0400",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003efor anyone looking for politically-based/anti-spiritual theory on ambient[yay!], i was just handed a copy of \u0026#34;din\u0026#34;, which is a collection of essaysavailable from:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePublic Works Administration Press\u003cbr\u003e1680 North Vine Street\u003cbr\u003eSuite 1118\u003cbr\u003eLos Angeles, CA  90028\u003cbr\u003eUSA\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe book is credited to Ultra-Red, who is Dont (pron. \u0026#34;Don\u0026#34;) Rhine, who\u003cbr\u003esome of you may know as a club promoter from LA. Most of the essays werepreviously published in CONTACT: EARTH ORBIT RENDEZVOUS, the newsletter ofPUBLIC SPACE, and the PUBLIC WORKS ADMINISTRATION [that\u0027s what it says inthe book... i don\u0027t know how to get those publications]. The tone is\u003cbr\u003epost-Modern and Marxist, trying to define ambient\u0027s social contexts of\u003cbr\u003eproduction and the concept of individual placement.(Some parts are still alittle too romantic for me - maintaining the concept of \u0026#34;revolution\u0026#34; andthe potential for a materialist \u0026#34;conciousness\u0026#34;....)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI\u0027m afraid no pricing or phone is given. Will post more info if i get it (Iknow Dont is living in NY now, since he just handed me it a couple hoursago, so there might be a NY address or phone to contact as well).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e     Terre Thaemlitz\u003cbr\u003e     terremt@med.cornell.edu\u003cbr\u003e     http://www2.med.cornell.edu/~terremt/Thaemlitz.html\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_09_125":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Sorry to bug y\u0027all about this but....",
                          "from":  "Jason Bunston \u003cjbunston@comp.uark.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Sat, 24 Sep 1994 10:36:46 -0500 (CDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOn Sat, 24 Sep 1994, Sean Smith wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e ...i have a question......\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003e I haven\u0027t bought an ambient CD is a while and since I\u0027ll soon be getting a\u003cbr\u003e\u003e job, I\u0027ll have the funds to start back up on my collecting.  My question\u003cbr\u003e\u003e is: would any of you care to give me a Top 10 of the all-time greatest\u003cbr\u003e\u003e ambient CDs for any collection?  I thought, with such a conglomeration of\u003cbr\u003e\u003e people who love what i love, I\u0027m bound to get some great recommendations\u003cbr\u003e\u003e for stuff I don\u0027t have.\u003cbr\u003e\t\u003cbr\u003e\tWell, not that my collection is all that encompassing, but if you \u003cbr\u003ewant the obvious choices that are easy to find, these will do perfectly:\u003cbr\u003e\tBarramundi:A Cooler World--Sampler from Astralwerks\u003cbr\u003e\tFrom Here to Tranquility I \u0026 II--Very good compilations with nice \u003cbr\u003e        \tcross sections of ambient styles\u003cbr\u003e\tAnything by Future Sound of London/Amorphous Androgonous\u003cbr\u003e\tThe Excursions in Ambience Series (1 to 3)--Again from \u003cbr\u003e                Astralwerks, with good variations in ambient styles\u003cbr\u003e\t\u003cbr\u003e\tI find the best way to start a collection is to hit the \u003cbr\u003ecompilations first--that way if you get a shitty CD, then you wind up \u003cbr\u003ewith a few good songs out of it. If you like the whole damn thing then \u003cbr\u003eits a bonus. I usually have a limited budget and search out the groups or individuals whose works I heard from samplers. I haven\u0027t wasted any money on bad albums yet--mind, if you don\u0027t mind spending 800$ then you won\u0027t mind getting a bad one here and there. (oh yeah--and the orb albums and mixes are killer too, but _everybody_ knows the orb so I left it out.)\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
