  "amb_1994_10_184":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: 99% have NO chance! - high fi equip ",
                          "from":  "Mad Gil \u003ccyberpun@wam.umd.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Sun, 16 Oct 1994 20:54:46 -0400 (EDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eOn Sun, 16 Oct 1994 fms@MIT.EDU wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003e Up until a few years ago, with the invention of dat tapes, i believe that\u003cbr\u003e\u003e all cd\u0027s were mastered off of video tapes.  the data frame size of a\u003cbr\u003e\u003e compact disc was chosen in part because it was compatible with the frame\u003cbr\u003e\u003e size of a video cassette (data on a videotape is written in diagonal lines\u003cbr\u003e\u003e across the tape rather than in a long stream along the tape, very strange).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI believe this is incorrect.  From what I remember, the way that a VHS \u003cbr\u003eVCR encodes stereo sound is the same way as FM-Stereo.  So it has the L-R and the R-L signals and can add or subtract to get the the original L and R, but I think where this falls short is that you can only record up to 17 or 18 KHz and I know that the low end on many VCRs is around 70 Hz, so it might be good for a low of music, but not for very full-frequency music.\u003cbr\u003e-Gil\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
