  "amb_1994_10_101":  {
                          "subject":  "Drone essentials",
                          "from":  "Dave Manning \u003cdmanning@cwis.unomaha.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Wed, 12 Oct 1994 20:06:51 -0500 (CDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis was posted to the seemingly defunct hypnodrone list last year. As\u003cbr\u003eyou\u0027ll see, some of the artists definitely cross over.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eFrom dan@gnu.ai.mit.edu Tue Feb 23 15:26:19 1993\u003cbr\u003eDate: Mon, 22 Feb 93 13:27:35 EST\u003cbr\u003eFrom: dan@gnu.ai.mit.edu\u003cbr\u003eTo: hypnodrone@gnu.ai.mit.edu\u003cbr\u003eSubject: *THE* essential\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eMy essentials would be (in roughly chronological order):\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eFairport Convention, Liege and Lief - This album\u0027s fame is that it\u0027s\u003cbr\u003econsidered the first English \u0026#34;folk-rock\u0026#34; album, but it\u0027s also a\u003cbr\u003eclassic droner!  From the swirling majesty of \u0026#34;Reynardine\u0026#34; to the true\u003cbr\u003edronitude of \u0026#34;Matty Groves\u0026#34; (which starts off as two chords and\u003cbr\u003eresolves to one) this one\u0027s for the ages.  Stark, otherworldly, etc.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eThe Velvet Underground, The Velvet Underground (the third album) -\u003cbr\u003eMore folk-rock, but with fabulous, essential stuff like \u0026#34;What Goes\u003cbr\u003eOn\u0026#34;, with it\u0027s fantastic guitar drone that set an example for a\u003cbr\u003egeneration.  All VU albums are great.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eMike Oldfield, Hergest Ridge - Tubular Bells set the tone, but HR is\u003cbr\u003esimpler, gentler and far more listenable in the long run.  Dense\u003cbr\u003e--More--(43%)\u003cbr\u003esounds, utterly simple music.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eBrian Eno, Music For Airports - One of the few albums by a \u0026#34;pop\u003cbr\u003etheorist\u0026#34; that\u0027s actually any good.  Highly listenable at any level of\u003cbr\u003eattention.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eRichard and Linda Thompson, Pour Down Like Silver - borderline drone,\u003cbr\u003ebut on the basis of \u0026#34;Night Comes In\u0026#34;, \u0026#34;Dimming of the Day\u0026#34; and even\u003cbr\u003esome of the straightforward songs, there\u0027s a droney, otherworldly\u003cbr\u003equality that seems to send me to the same place as other classics of\u003cbr\u003ethe genre.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eSpacemen 3, The Perfect Prescription - Perfect is right.  A gentle\u003cbr\u003ebreeze that sometimes turns into a firey inferno and comes right back.\u003cbr\u003eA genuinely spiritual album, with thoughtful lyrics and a deep\u003cbr\u003eemotional resonance.  Perhaps one of the finest manifestos on the\u003cbr\u003epleasures and perils of drug use, but you don\u0027t need drugs to enjoy\u003cbr\u003eit (they\u0027ve taken them for you!).  Eclectic in all the right ways\u003cbr\u003e(going from the serene nirvana of \u0026#34;Feels So Good\u0026#34; to the swirling hell\u003cbr\u003eof \u0026#34;Things Won\u0027t Be the Same\u0026#34; is inspired and doesn\u0027t seem merely\u003cbr\u003esnotty).  It\u0027s an album that rewards extensive listening.  I didn\u0027t\u003cbr\u003ereally notice the very final lines of the song \u0026#34;Walking With Jesus\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003euntil about the 30th listen (it\u0027s deep in the mix, but audible).\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eSpacemen 3, Playing With Fire - Who\u0027d have thought it possible?  One\u003cbr\u003eyear later, and an album that\u0027s almost as good as PP, but totally\u003cbr\u003edifferent!  This album\u0027s tone is even more overtly spiritual and\u003cbr\u003econfessional, but none the less confrontational in its intent.  It\u0027s\u003cbr\u003emore \u0026#34;difficult\u0026#34; listening than PP, but over time, it reveals itself\u003cbr\u003eas accesible.  It\u0027s fitting that this album should feature the\u003cbr\u003eSpacemen at both their prettiest (\u0026#34;Come Down Softly to My Soul\u0026#34;,\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;Honey\u0026#34;) and their most harsh and atonal (\u0026#34;Revolution\u0026#34;, \u0026#34;Suicide\u0026#34;).\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eGalaxie 500, This is Our Music - All three Galaxie albums are\u003cbr\u003eessential, but this is my favorite.  Every song is a winner, from the\u003cbr\u003egoofy charm of the opening (\u0026#34;I wrote a poem on a dog biscuit, but the\u003cbr\u003edog refused to look at it, so I got drunk and watched the Empire\u003cbr\u003eState Building.  It was no bigger than a nickle\u0026#34;) to the Beatlesque\u003cbr\u003esweeetness of \u0026#34;King of Spain Part 2\u0026#34;.  Dean\u0027s guitar never sounded\u003cbr\u003ebetter, Damon\u0027s drumming is ace, and Naomi, the true soul of the band,\u003cbr\u003eis in tip-top form both in her melodic, trebly bass-playing and her\u003cbr\u003egorgeous vocals on \u0026#34;Listen the Snow is Falling\u0026#34;.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eThe Darkside, All That Noise - Some might argue that this record,\u003cbr\u003ethough great, is simply TOO close a pastiche of the classic\u003cbr\u003epsychedelic era.  But there\u0027s a lot more than ust that.  \u0026#34;Waiting For\u003cbr\u003ethe Angels\u0026#34; is quite \u0026#34;modern\u0026#34; sounding, and a scorcher at that.  I\u003cbr\u003ealso like that when they\u0027re derivative, they\u0027re very obvious about it,\u003cbr\u003eas in \u0026#34;Soul Deep\u0026#34; (which has entirely \u0026#34;found\u0026#34; lyrics I think - can\u003cbr\u003eanyone name them all?) rather than the coy appropriation of say, The\u003cbr\u003eCharlatans.  This album is just dripping with atmosphere, a kind\u003cbr\u003eof smoky, rainy-night, smelling of bourbon and marijuana and cheap\u003cbr\u003efloozies in London or Las Vegas.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eSpiritualized, Lazer Guided Melodies - How sweet it is.  Jason adds\u003cbr\u003ehorns and strings, tightens up the sound (Spiritualized is more like a\u003cbr\u003echamber ensemble than a rock group, really!) and produces a full, rich\u003cbr\u003esound that envelopes and embraces you.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eSpectrum, Soul Kiss (Glide Divine) - More warmth and love from Sonic\u003cbr\u003eBoom.  Sonic has found new sounds and a more \u0026#34;mature\u0026#34; compositional\u003cbr\u003estyle, and it works a charm.  At times the record is almost \u0026#34;new age\u0026#34;,\u003cbr\u003ebut what new age album would have a drug/ecstasy anthem like \u0026#34;How You\u003cbr\u003eSatisfy Me\u0026#34; on it?  Yanni and Kitaro run screaming.  Sonic has never\u003cbr\u003eforgotten that great squalling feedback is still a component of this\u003cbr\u003esort of thing.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003eDamon and Naomi, More Sad Hits - Maybe it\u0027s just because it\u0027s new, but\u003cbr\u003eI think this is a classic in the field, and feels tantalizingly like a\u003cbr\u003efourth Galaxie 500 album.  I\u0027ve raved about it before, but the song\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;This Car Climbed Mt. Washington\u0026#34;, to me, sums up hypnodrone\u003cbr\u003eperfectly.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e---\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDrone on,\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDave\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e.----------------------------------------------dmanning@dreamland.unomaha.edu |    \u0026#34;Heaven knows it\u0027s got to be this time.\u0026#34; dmanning@cwis.unomaha.edu |                                             dmanning@eworld.com\u003cbr\u003e.-------------------------------------------- dgmanning@aol.com\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
