  "amb_1994_10_198":  {
                          "subject":  "\u0027EMPHASIS\u0027 on CDs, and Woob",
                          "from":  "Paddy Grove \u003cgrove@cpd.ntc.nokia.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Mon, 17 Oct 1994 10:46:44 +0100",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHi all, \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e    Not directly ambient related, but kinda, and we have been talking hi-fistuff here..\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e    My Denon CD playe has a LEd indicator \u0027EMPHASIS\u0027 which I\u0027ve only everseen come on for one CD before. Then I bought a couple of discs at the\u003cbr\u003eweekend, and it comes on for both of them - they\u0027re _Woob 1194_  and _AmbiantOtaku_ (Tetsu Inoue). Anyone know what \u0027emphasis\u0027 means. It seems to be\u003cbr\u003esomething encoded on the disc, rather than the player deciding for itself,since it comes up instantly without the disc being scanned or anything. Forthe record, the old disc that showed it was Roger Waters \u0026#34;Pros \u0026 Cons ofHitch-hiking\u0026#34; (thus re-introducing the Pink Floyd thread :))\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e    Both discs are good, BTW, but the Woob is just excellent -my idea of howambient should sound. Tracks that develop and mutate without overdone\u003cbr\u003erepetition, controlled use of samples; Love those tree frog sounds! :). Howdoes the em:t0094 compare, anyone? After the ravings on here about AmbiantOtaku, I\u0027m a little disappointed, but maybe it\u0027ll grow on me like Sad World 2did.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e    That\u0027ll do for now,\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e        Paddy\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOnNow: Woob1194, track 2 \u0026#34;odonna\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
