  "amb_1994_10_66":  {
                         "subject":  "Tinty Music _Compromise_ Review",
                         "from":  "AMBIENCE@delphi.com",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 11 Oct 1994 23:40:22 -0400 (EDT)",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eTinty Music - _Compromise_\u003cbr\u003eFormat: Cassette\u003cbr\u003eTotal Running Time: Approximately 88 minutes\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSide A:\u003cbr\u003e1) Transparency #1 (Sky blue and jet black) 7:56 (July 1, 1994)\u003cbr\u003e2) Transparency #2 (Awake yet dreaming) 13:49 (July 6, 1994)\u003cbr\u003e3) Mind The Gap (20:32) (March 24, 1994)\u003cbr\u003e4) The Flickering Flame (3:27) (June 1992)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSide B:\u003cbr\u003e1) Transparency #3 (Mapping the forest of forgotten dreams) 46:21 (July 7,1994)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  _Compromise_ is a recording by Kevin O\u0027Conner, which features selectionsfrom a future CD release _Transparency_, except for \u0026#34;Mind The Gap\u0026#34; that\u003cbr\u003ewill be on his upcoming _Weightlessness: Of Contemplation \u0026 Distraction_ CD,and \u0026#34;The Flickering Flame\u0026#34; that is available only on this recording. Thescheduled release date for _Transparency_ is unknown at this time.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  In the liner notes, Kevin writes: \u0026#34;The music contained in this cassettealbum is intended as ambient music in the truest sense of the term, its\u003cbr\u003epurpose essentially being to exist as aural wallpaper. It is intended\u003cbr\u003eneither to be soothing, nor boring.....it\u0027s effect on you, the listener,will determine it\u0027s ultimate use.\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  Ambient music indeed. Transparency #1, and #2 are long droning soundscapesreminiscent of Steve Roach circa _Structures From Silence_. To these\u003cbr\u003esoundscapes, are added bell sounds that conjure up the images of TUU\u0027s _OneThousand Years_. Very soothing, and tranceful. \u0026#34;Mind The Gap\u0026#34; samples what Iassume to be a voice in a train station telling passengers to \u0026#34;mind the\u003cbr\u003egap\u0026#34;. This sample gets annoying after a while, but luckily it\u0027s used\u003cbr\u003eintermittently. Train sounds politely brush up to the forefront, and thendrift backwards. Meanwhile, a very icy drone lays the backdrop for the\u003cbr\u003eentire piece. It whispers, growing louder, and then receding again. I foundthe effect of the droning sounds to be hypnotic when played at loud levels.\u0026#34;The Flickering Flame\u0026#34; is a short piece that is much louder than the\u003cbr\u003epredecessors. Somewhat disjointed, with various sounds popping in and out.\u003cbr\u003e  \u0026#34;Transparency #3\u0026#34; is ambitious. Once again, ambient droning soundscapeslay the backdrop and various bell sounds, and other ringing percussion\u003cbr\u003efilters in and out. I picture myself in a winter cavern, and the wind isswirling back and forth creating a hallowed effect. Very well done, but itduplicates \u0026#34;Transparency #2\u0026#34;. Plus, at 46+ minutes, it goes of too long.But, if the desired effect is background music, then it\u0027s a success. Yourmileage may vary.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  Overall, very promising, and his CD should be interesting.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e  For further information, you can reach Kevin at tintmeister@pan.com ortntmusic@halcyon.com.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e____________________________________________________________________________Paul Rafanello                                           ambience@delphi.com____________________________________________________________________________\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
  "amb_1994_09_81":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: cheap \u0027n dirty surround sound a la Eno",
                         "from":  "Michael Joly \u003celectric@world.std.com\u003e",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 20 Sep 1994 22:42:57 +0059 (EDT)",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOn Tue, 20 Sep 1994, Mike Brown wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003e Can someone post or e-mail me the liner notes from the early Brian Eno \u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003e album that told of a way to hook up a third speaker for a sort of \u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003e low-budget, pseudo-surround-sound effect? I thought it was on one of his \u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003e early ambient albums, some time before Apollo I guess.\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003cbr\u003eIt\u0027s really ok to add a third \u0026#34;ambience recovery\u0026#34; speaker to a stereo \u003cbr\u003eset-up if the third speaker is at least 8 Ohms impedance. (Usually marked on the back).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYour amplifier back panel should state that it can drive a minimum load of 4 Ohms. (Generally stated as \u0026#34;speaker load: 4 - 16 Ohms\u0026#34;)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe third speaker is hooked across the left and right (+) terminals \u003cbr\u003e(usually red in color).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis third speaker, wired in this fashion, will only reproduce the \u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;difference\u0026#34; information between left and right channels. That is, you\u0027ll hear left, right and \u0026#34;surround\u0026#34; information which consists mostly of \u003cbr\u003ereverberation effects from \u0026#34;front\u0026#34; channel instruments.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTry pointing the third speaker toward the back of your listening room or at the ceiling to increase diffusion and spatially differentiate the \u003cbr\u003esound of ambience speaker from the main stereo pair.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHave fun, it\u0027s cheap and cool.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMichael Joly\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;ElectricSpace\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003eWMBR 88.1 Cambridge, MA\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
