                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e------------------------------\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eFrom: Dave Walker \u003cmarmoset@garnet.msen.com\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eDate: Thu, 20 Oct 1994 11:41:36 -0400 (EDT)\u003cbr\u003e\u003eSubject: Re: Namlook / Aphex\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eOn Tue, 18 Oct 1994, Ken Stuart wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003e I don\u0027t think that Richard James is missing some characteristic of \u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003e Namlook, or vice versa.  But they might make a good album, nonetheless.\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eThat being said, I\u0027d have to name Namlook as one of the most \u0026#34;consistent\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e\u003ecollaborators around these days -- for example, I wouldn\u0027t hesitate to\u003cbr\u003e\u003ecall his collaboration with Richie Hawtin one of the top releases of the \u003cbr\u003e\u003eyear -- it perfectly plays off of the strengths of both, though they\u0027re\u003cbr\u003e\u003ecoming from very different directions musically.  In fact, in general \u003cbr\u003e\u003eI\u0027ve found Namlook\u0027s collaborations more interesting than his solo stuff.\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eOnNow: Philip Glass - \u0026#34;Music In Fifths\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYou know that Namlook just did a collaboration with Klause Schultz.\u003cbr\u003e\u003e- -----------------------------------------------------------------\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e Nick Philip  SFX Labo\u003cbr\u003e 101 Townsend st, #270\u003cbr\u003e San Francisco,\u003cbr\u003e Ca 94107\u003cbr\u003ePhone:415-896-5628\u003cbr\u003eFax 415-896-5629\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
