  "amb_1994_11_136":  {
                          "subject":  "three reviews",
                          "from":  "jsd@cyborganic.com (Jon Drukman)",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 18 Nov 1994 15:19:21 -40962758 (PST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003eFrom Here To Tranquility Vol 3\u003cbr\u003eSilent Records SR9460\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWell, no surprises here.  It reminds me of Vol 1 in the series, which\u003cbr\u003eI didn\u0027t like that much (even though I myself had contributed), more\u003cbr\u003ethan Vol 2, which is a shame.  Floaty stuff with very little to hook\u003cbr\u003eonto.  Doesn\u0027t grab me.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnother Fine Day: \u0026#34;Life Before Land\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003eBeyond Records RBADCD7\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis is a different story!  This is a wild, amazing trip into realms\u003cbr\u003ehitherto left unexplored by ambient creators.  Spacy and electronic,\u003cbr\u003ewith deep FSOL-esque synth blasts wrapped around almost jazzy acoustic\u003cbr\u003esounding stuff.  There\u0027s some upright bass and flute parts that sound\u003cbr\u003ereal.  Probably are, for all I know.  Great melodies, great rhythms\u003cbr\u003efrom time to time.  I love it.  Also don\u0027t miss their track Wild\u003cbr\u003eSpirit Of Song, on Ambient Dub Volume 3 - easily the highlight of that\u003cbr\u003ealbum.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis disc leaves me full of optimism - it\u0027s not cliched or hackneyed\u003cbr\u003ein the least.  It manages to be very electronic yet still retain a\u003cbr\u003ehuman touch.  A joy from start to end.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTangerine Dream: \u0026#34;Tangents\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003eVirgin CDBOX 4\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTangerine Dream were always quite prolific, and this box set showcases\u003cbr\u003etheir most productive and creatively successful periods - the Virgin\u003cbr\u003eRecords era, 1973-1983.  It\u0027s five CDs worth of original tracks,\u003cbr\u003erecreated versions of old tracks, soundtracks and previously\u003cbr\u003eunreleased material all wrapped in a stunning Buggy G.\u003cbr\u003eRiphead-designed box.  Obviously something that covers such a wide\u003cbr\u003erange will have wildly variable contents, but I personally find about\u003cbr\u003e75% of the material to be worthwhile, which is a very respectable\u003cbr\u003eratio.  If you\u0027ve already got all the Virgin CDs, this might be\u003cbr\u003eredundant, but for someone like me who was looking for a good way to\u003cbr\u003ereplace a lot of worn vinyl, this is a great deal.  An ideal present\u003cbr\u003efor the space music fan in your life.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOh, and if you\u0027ve never checked out the Dream, this is a pretty decent\u003cbr\u003eintroduction.  My one complaint is that it misses off some of the\u003cbr\u003ereally trancy synth pieces (like \u0026#34;Thru Metamorphic Rocks\u0026#34;) in favor of\u003cbr\u003emore melodic material, but we can\u0027t have everything...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJon Drukman                                                 jsd@cyborganic.com------------------------------------------------------------------------------Things are more like they are now than they ever were before.\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_09_57":  {
                         "subject":  "Tetsu Inoue",
                         "from":  "terremt@mail.med.cornell.edu (Terre Thaemlitz)",
                         "dateString":  "Mon, 19 Sep 1994 15:41:14 -0400",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003eFrom: gamshad@tcs.com (Mohsen Gamshad)\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eMy listening list these days:\u003cbr\u003e\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e1) Tetsu Inue:   Ambient Otaku (FAX)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003esp:      [Inoue] [Ambiant]\u003cbr\u003e            ^         ^\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis cd is currently at the top of my list as well (which doesn\u0027t get\u003cbr\u003echanged that often). For those of you thinking of tetsu\u0027s trance work (Om,etc.), Ambiant Otaku is straight-ahead deep ambient. The last track is mypersonal favorite, and I have been putting it in many of my sets lately.However, I think tetsu\u0027s favorite is the second track (that\u0027s the one hetold me to check out when he first gave me a copy).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI think tetsu is one of the most talented people i know - probably THE\u003cbr\u003emost. He\u0027s been doing ambient-trance since the late 80\u0027s, before it became\u0027hot\u0027, and i truly hope he ends up receiving the visibility he deserves.\u003cbr\u003ebtw: for those of you in the nyc area, tetsu and I have been doing dj-esquesets around town every now and then. he\u0027s in germany right now working onnew material with pete n., but we\u0027ll be performing together at the Kitchenon Nov. 4 \u0026 5 as part of the global Electronic Cafe event, which FSOL issupposed to do some sort of broadcast from the UK for, I think. [I believethere is also a SF Electronic Cafe, among other places. The idea is thatall of these places around the world will be having events and telecastingthem to one another. I think there will also be net connections.]\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eciaoforniao\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e     Terre Thaemlitz\u003cbr\u003e     terremt@med.cornell.edu\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
