  "amb_1994_09_16":  {
                         "subject":  "Re: labels-n-such",
                         "from":  "\"Finlayson / Gordon Stanley (COM)\" \u003cu912288@student.canberra.edu.au\u003e",
                         "dateString":  "Tue, 13 Sep 1994 14:10:42 +1000 (EST)",
                         "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eA couple of questions and ne answer from one of those who subscribed in the last 24 hours...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFor a start, I\u0027m not sure about the others, but I stumbled across the \u003cbr\u003elist address when I was wondering around the hyperreal gopher.  So, no \u003cbr\u003eleads there. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSituated in the ambient desert of Canberra, Australia, I must admit that definitions on the list pose a few questions for me.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIn his posting, Robert quoted Delerium\u0027s After 6am label as qualifying \u003cbr\u003eas ambient, but the only one of those records that I have (Solar Eclipse) I would have given as trance, so I was wondering where ambient really \u003cbr\u003ebegins, and consequently where this list stops?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eg.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                     },
  "amb_1994_10_456":  {
                          "subject":  "The dark side of the ... genre",
                          "from":  "Dave Manning \u003cdmanning@cwis.unomaha.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Sat, 29 Oct 1994 22:37:33 -0500 (CDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHi all.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMy subscription to the indie-rock mag _Alternative Press_ finally caughtup with me, and while their electronic coverage (\u0026#34;BPM\u0026#34;) is usually fairlysparse, they did have two reviews that got me thinking.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFirst off is another studio release by God. No, not *that* God; we\u0027re\u003cbr\u003etalking jazz-heavy Kevin Martin and ten of his closest friends. This is\u003cbr\u003enot your average Harold Budd/Pat Metheny ambient - it\u0027s probably closer toScorn, E.A.R, and the rest of the roster of Earache who got tired of doingspeedcore. From the review alone, I want this record, but not to fall\u003cbr\u003easleep to.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSecond on the AP review tip is a compilation called _Isolationism -\u003cbr\u003eAmbient IV_, a double-disc on Virgin which is presumably the latest in\u003cbr\u003etheir Ambient series. And I think this one\u0027s a wee bit different, with\u003cbr\u003etracks from Scorn, Ice (another Kevin Martin creation), Main, Seefeel,\u003cbr\u003eAphex Twin (natch), and Labradford, to name a few. From the line-up, thistoo sounds like a winner.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNow, to the point: It\u0027s important to realize ambient\u0027s soothing\u003cbr\u003eproperties, its dreamy qualities, ambient should also scare, terrify,\u003cbr\u003ehumiliate, and exhilarate *as well* as sooth. In an e-mail exchange with amainstream techno/ambient artist who will remain nameless (Moby), I askedhim what he thought a second ambient release by him would contain. The\u003cbr\u003eanswer: \u0026#34;Maybe a shoe in a dryer for a few minutes.\u0026#34; Personally, I thinkit would work.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSo, the moral of this somewhat directionless tirade is that there\u0027s moreto ambient than Tangerine Dream, FAX, Harold Budd, or shoes. I, for one,am going to make a point of picking up some of these non-mainstream\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;ambient\u0026#34; releases, because it\u0027s good for me, has plenty of vitamins, andwon\u0027t cause this list to become totally \u0026#34;Artificial\u0026#34; like the IDM list.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIMHO, of course, and after more than my fair share of hot chocolate,\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDave\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e.------------------------------------------dave.manning@dreamland.unomaha.edu |    \u0026#34;Station\u0027s starting to fade...\u0026#34;          dmanning@cwis.unomaha.edu |                                             dmanning@eworld.com\u003cbr\u003e.-------------------------------------------- dgmanning@aol.com\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_11_207":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Rob\u0027t Rich \"Propagation\" -- disappointed",
                          "from":  "jsd@cyborganic.com (Jon Drukman)",
                          "dateString":  "Mon, 21 Nov 1994 17:47:41 -40962758 (PST)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eJens Alfke writes:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e Remember when I was asking for Robert Rich recommendations? I finally picked\u003cbr\u003e\u003e up \u0026#34;Propagation\u0026#34; and was pretty disappointed. Instead of the flowing iciness\u003cbr\u003e\u003e of \u0026#34;Liquid Air\u0026#34; (on \u0026#34;From Here To Tranquility\u0026#34; #2) there is a lot of\u003cbr\u003e\u003e faux-Asian percussion and koto laid on.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIt\u0027s real Asian percussion and koto.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e If I could strip that stuff off the\u003cbr\u003e\u003e mix the rest might be more like what I was looking for, but the overall\u003cbr\u003e\u003e effect was too similar to the Japanese Muzak they play in sushi bars.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eGee, my favorite sushi bar plays aphex twin, peter gabriel\u0027s\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;passion\u0026#34;, zoviet france and lustmord.  Oh yeah, and Robert Rich.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e Are any of his other releases more ambient? (_Much_ more ambient?)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTry \u0026#34;Soma\u0026#34; with Steve Roach.  And \u0026#34;Numena\u0026#34; if you want \u0026#34;real\u0026#34; ambient.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI had a conversation with Bob just last week and he said it was a\u003cbr\u003eshame that everyone was so hung up on his early stuff (eg: Numena).\u003cbr\u003eHis comment was like \u0026#34;I don\u0027t know why i bother trying new stuff when\u003cbr\u003epeople are just catching on to what i was doing 15 years ago.\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHe\u0027s also got a double CD of old stuff out on Extreme - called\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;Trances \u0026 Drones\u0026#34;, probably more of what you\u0027re looking for.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJon Drukman\u003cbr\u003ejsd@cyborganic.com\u003cbr\u003e------------------------------------------------------------------------------Things are more like they are now than they ever were before.\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_177":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Seefeel _Pure,_Impure_",
                          "from":  "jjdavis@xnet.com (Jeff Davis)",
                          "dateString":  "Sat, 15 Oct 1994 22:21:12 -0600",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e|On Fri, 14 Oct 1994, Alan Scully wrote (re Seefeel Pure_Impure):\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI must AGREE....\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e|  The Aphex mixes are pretty \u003cbr\u003e|decent,\u003cbr\u003eI love the AFX slow mix , it\u0027s scrumpdubbylishus.  Even listened too\u003cbr\u003eimmediately after the AFS fast mix, it still kicks it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e| but the real gem is the plainsong sine bubble embossed dub which \u003cbr\u003e|was remixed by autocreation. \u003cbr\u003ethis mix is one of those ever so cool mixes that are fully morphed to\u003cbr\u003ethe point where you can\u0027t really make out the original tune.  It starts\u003cbr\u003eoff with just a pulsing bubble which continues to intensify.  My\u003cbr\u003efavorite track off polyfusia.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJeff Davis              ____--~~~~~~vvvv~~~~        oo                   jjdavis@xnet.com____----   (   (   ( vvvv ~~~~~~ooooooooooo  \u003cbr\u003e         ___----(   (   \\   \\   \\   \\   \\vvv   oooooooooooooo    815.772.1260____---- (   \\   \\   \\   \\   \\   \\   \\   \\ vvooooooooooooooooooooo\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
