  "amb_1994_10_100":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: Spectrum?",
                          "from":  "Dave Manning \u003cdmanning@cwis.unomaha.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Wed, 12 Oct 1994 19:59:43 -0500 (CDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSpectrum is primarily the brainchild of former Spaceman Sonic Boom (PeteKember/aka Pete Spaceman) who has recorded under the Sonic Boom name andSpectrum (as a band). Where Jason Pierce with Spiritualized has producedwhat could be called \u0027big-band\u0027 jazz/drone rock, Sonic Boom (with help\u003cbr\u003efrom Richard Formby, who was in the Darkside), has done some more\u003cbr\u003eintrospective work. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAs is true with \u0026#34;rock\u0026#34; bands with two strong creative axes, Spaceman 3\u0027smusic was (IMHO) nearly evenly divided between Sonic Boom\u0027s and Jason\u003cbr\u003ePierce\u0027s creative works. Spectrum is more introspective, and the _Soul\u003cbr\u003eKiss (Glide Divine)_ album is a must. Actually, Spaceman 3 is a must, Jens- which albums have you been disappointed in?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDave\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e.----------------------------------------------dmanning@dreamland.unomaha.edu |    \u0026#34;Heaven knows it\u0027s got to be this time.\u0026#34; dmanning@cwis.unomaha.edu |                                             dmanning@eworld.com\u003cbr\u003e.-------------------------------------------- dgmanning@aol.com\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_187":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: one of the 99%",
                          "from":  "Number19@aol.com",
                          "dateString":  "Sun, 16 Oct 1994 21:42:49 -0400",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eJust had to say I agree with everything Mad Gil said. Don, be careful aboutimposing your standards on others. I consistently plan to upgrade my\u003cbr\u003eequipment, but I usually opt to buy more music instead in the hopes I find abagful of money to buy a new turntable. So am I a bad listener because Ichoose to support the bands by buying their music -- but I\u0027m insulting themby not listening to their records with the correct stereo equipment?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAs far as headphones go, my favorite listening scenario goes like this:\u003cbr\u003eSelect some ambient/trancey/jazzy-type thang. Put the headphones on. Lightthe incense and candles, get comfy in my easy chair and chill with the volumemoderately loud.\u003cbr\u003eAt work I listen to all genres, but especially ambient/trancey/jazzy-typethangs, through my shitty Mac speakers or my shitty jambox -- On the road,though my 7-year-old cheap speakers behind the bench seat of my pick-up, asloud and cone-cracklin\u0027 as possible.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePeace, 19.\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
