  "amb_1994_09_173":  {
                          "subject":  "Maintream and Ambient",
                          "from":  "Michael Joly \u003celectric@world.std.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Thu, 29 Sep 1994 13:44:30 +0059 (EDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003e I can\u0027t think of many ambient tracks in my collection that stand very \u003cbr\u003e\u003e steadily under the 8-10min range.  How then could a music industry that \u003cbr\u003e\u003e thrives on tracks that mainly sit in the 3-5min range be able to cope \u003cbr\u003e\u003e with this type of music without one of the two having to undergo rather \u003cbr\u003e\u003e drastic changes.  Broadcasting ambient is problematic enough when taking \u003cbr\u003e\u003e into account the loss of quality sustained, even when the time and will \u003cbr\u003e\u003e exists to put full length tracks to air.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\tSince I\u0027m in an expansive and optimistic mood these days I\u0027d \u003cbr\u003elike to suggest that those of us who spin on radio shows, in clubs and \u003cbr\u003ecafes double our efforts to grow an audience for ambient and eventually influence \u0026#34;the industry\u0026#34;. Here\u0027s why I think it could work.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAt the risk of overgeneralizing, I think many people listen to particular radio stations or on-air dj\u0027s do so because because that station or dj \u003cbr\u003esupplys a predictable sonic soundscape that somehow fits into a listener\u0027s life. An ambience.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe use of sound broadcast over commercial radio is, to a great extent, a background to activities like study, work, and conversation. So, many \u003cbr\u003elisteners are already practice a style of listening that is not \u003cbr\u003eincompatable with ambient music.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOf course the type of stuff that dominates pop and alternative charts is a very different sound - sex desire/loss vocal or postmodern ironic vocal angst. But these are typical expressions of Western individualistic culture.\u003cbr\u003ePerhaps the emergence of a post industrial/post colonial global community awarness will also bring a need for music that is more contemplative and inclusive of various cultural expressions - ambient music.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSo I\u0027m all for storming the bastions of \u0026#34;the way it is now\u0026#34;.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eRespectfully,\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eOne of many sonic warriors,\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSoundman MJ\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;ElectricSpace\u0026#34; WMBR 88.1\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_09_182":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: AMBIENT IS DEAD",
                          "from":  "rbcIII \u003crobot@svpal.org\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Thu, 29 Sep 1994 15:17:15 -0700 (PDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNaw I don\u0027t buy the whole \u0026#34;since RDJ, Namlook... don\u0027t stand up in the \u003cbr\u003emedia then they\u0027re not what they\u0027re knocked up to be\u0026#34; trash.  Could it be that when the media all of a sudden jumped on them they hated it?  Anyone who is truly dedicated to the \u0026#34;underground\u0026#34; would, right?  If I was an \u003cbr\u003eovernight sensation I would blurt out nonsense to get the media off my back too.  Everything I ever read that featured \u0026#34;The Aphex Twin\u0026#34; was some \u003cbr\u003echeaply rewritten press release anyway.  The actual interviews with RDJ were him saying nonsense about never sleeping and his girlfriend (not \u003cbr\u003emedia savvy material).  FSOL on the other hand are media pro\u0027s.  They \u003cbr\u003ealways say the right shit to make the press squirm.  They love FSOL.  \u003cbr\u003eThey\u0027re so pompous and pretentious.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eScenario.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eInterviewer:  So what made you decide to do something as radical as \u003cbr\u003e\t\t\u0026#34;Lifeforms\u0026#34;?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDougans \u0026 Cobain: Because we\u0027re too cool for dance music.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eC\u0027mon Lifeforms is not that much of a departure from Accelerator.  Plus their dance music is better anyway.  I do give FSOL credit for continuing to change.  I just don\u0027t see it as being as far out as they make it out to be.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFAX is the best example of inconsistent music.  Some of it is pretty and new agey and some of it is hard and trancey.  Obvious signs of ambience on the moove.  Take a listen to Jonah Sharpe\u0027s stuff.  Space Time \u003cbr\u003eContinuum is always changing.  This whole \u0026#34;ambient is dead\u0026#34; issue sounds very ironic to me anyway.  Using media hype to declare the death of a \u003cbr\u003escene which rejects the media?\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eGO OUT AND BUY FFWD!!!  AND STOP MAKING ME POST ABOUT RDJ \u0026 FSOL DAMNIT!!!\u003cbr\u003e-robert\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
