  "amb_1994_10_142":  {
                          "subject":  "Cthuga one more time",
                          "from":  "eric@macaw.retix.com (Eric Walton\u0027s account)",
                          "dateString":  "Fri, 14 Oct 1994 08:42:26 -0700",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe recent flurry of posts about Cthuga and its ilk reminds me of a\u003cbr\u003eprogram called Kaleidoscope that I had back in 1981 on my Apple II.\u003cbr\u003eFeed in a sound source (music) and out would come a dancing kaleidoscopeon the screen. The colors and shape of the kaleidoscope would change\u003cbr\u003ein real time in response to the physical characteristics of the sound\u003cbr\u003ethat the Apple \u0026#34;heard\u0026#34;. It was OK for its day but I\u0027ve always wished\u003cbr\u003efor a more state of the art version of this that takes advantage\u003cbr\u003eof todays hardware MIPS and graphics prowess.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDoes anyone know whether a Macintosh version of Cthuga, Fractunes, \u003cbr\u003eMusic Mandala, etc. exists. If so, where can I get it? I\u0027m only\u003cbr\u003einterested in software that produces real time \u0026#34;interpretation\u0026#34;\u003cbr\u003e(e.g., interesting patterns, etc.) of an input sound source.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThanks\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eEric\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_11_117":  {
                          "subject":  "Re: live performance",
                          "from":  "\"Jens Alfke\" \u003cjens_alfke@powertalk.apple.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "16 Nov 1994 11:55:26 -0800",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eSpiros Antonopoulos asks:\u003cbr\u003e\u003ealso... how hard would it be to rig cheap sensors (like the light beam \u003cbr\u003e\u003esensor that dings a bell when you walk into radio shack by breaking the \u003cbr\u003e\u003ebeam... or cheap alarm system sensors) to trigger midi events so that the \u003cbr\u003e\u003eperformance *does* become decentralized \u0026 more interactive and dancers \u0026 \u003cbr\u003e\u003echillers can have their creative fill???????\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe Sound Traffic Control events last week in SF had something like this. Theentry hallway to the club had a plastic flooring with wires in it and\u003cbr\u003espeakers alongside; stepping in just the right place triggered various drumhits and beats. I fooled with it but was never clear exactly what the\u003cbr\u003econnection was between where I stepped and what sound came out, but there wasclearly a connection of some sort.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eJens Alfke ........ OpenDoc Mnemonist ....... jens_alfke@powertalk.apple.com\u003cbr\u003e   \u0026#34;Our soldiers are justified in wishing to bring proper justice to\u003cbr\u003e    these errant managers.\u0026#34;     --Xi Ten, Ministry of Economic Reform, China            after 18 factory managers were executed for poor product quality\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
