  "amb_1994_09_147":  {
                          "subject":  "Some thoughts re: Ambient is Over",
                          "from":  "Michael Joly \u003celectric@world.std.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Wed, 28 Sep 1994 19:00:03 +0059 (EDT)",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eWhat, so soon? \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePerhaps Dog\u0027s disenchantment with the ambient scene is a \u003cbr\u003ecomment on the accelerated pace of subculture formation and \u003cbr\u003edissolution that is most visible in the UK. It appears that as \u003cbr\u003esoon as a scene is identified it morphs into something \u003cbr\u003eunrecognizable or undesirable to the originating impulse.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eHere in the states on the other hand, because of the massive inertia of big business radio, television, film and to a lesser extent the \u003cbr\u003eclubs themselves - audiences are slow to recognize and acknowledge the \u003cbr\u003eappearance of new musical cultures.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAmbient has hardly started here. Mention ambient in the \u003cbr\u003estates and most people think you\u0027re talking about the \u003cbr\u003etemperature! Well, that may not be true in San Francisco, \u003cbr\u003eLA or New York - but in Boston (provincial yes, but not an \u003cbr\u003euncultured backwater) it really isn\u0027t happening yet.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eBut an audience is out there. Even though my radio show on \u003cbr\u003eWMBR is on late - 12:30 to 2:30AM on Tuesdays the \u003cbr\u003estation gets lots of calls from people wanting to know about \u003cbr\u003ethe music I\u0027m playing; who the artists and labels are. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf we could collectively convince some of the hundreds of \u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;Seattle Style\u0026#34; grunge cafes that are springing up all over \u003cbr\u003ethe place that the true alternative music is not yet another \u003cbr\u003emumble-mouthed angst driven guitar band - perhaps they \u003cbr\u003emight start playing ambient music and expose it to an \u003cbr\u003eaudience that exists outside of the clubs.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnd perhaps if, along with more truly alternative venues, \u003cbr\u003emore RADIO STATIONS would program the music we \u003cbr\u003emight witness an increase in the number of musician \u003cbr\u003eworking in and pushing the boundaries of the ambient styles.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSo I don\u0027t think ambient is over. I think we all have a lot of \u003cbr\u003ework to due to look after its growth.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003epeace, sincerely\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eMichael Joly \u0026#34;Soundman MJ\u0026#34; on  \u0026#34;ElectricSpace\u0026#34; WMBR 88.1 Cambridge, MA  "
                      },
