  "amb_1994_10_175":  {
                          "subject":  "Audiophile Phukwits",
                          "from":  "mr808@teleport.com",
                          "dateString":  "Sat, 15 Oct 1994 22:36:57 +0000",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e Don Weir \u003cdonweir@sydney.DIALix.oz.au\u003e wrote:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003eAnd then there is the reproduction equipment. The junk that is sold and\u003cbr\u003e\u003eaccepted by the public is a disgrace to the hearing senses. The $200 modular\u003cbr\u003e\u003ehifi\u0027s and $100 walkmans - what a joke! Then 95% who \u0027listen\u0027 to these are\u003cbr\u003e\u003eeither doing something or yakking away. They are not listening.  Really, there\u003cbr\u003e\u003eare very few individuals out there who\u0027ll spend money on hifi gear that\u003cbr\u003e\u003ereproduces the original sound faithfully. There are very few music lovers,\u003cbr\u003e\u003eindeed there are many who like it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAre you saying that since I\u0027m listening to a 10 year old, $200 Sony Discman(the first portable at a time when CD players were $600 minimum, 0X\u003cbr\u003eoversampling, takes multiple drops on concrete \u0026 keeps on tracking, albeitin a persnickety way), then I DON\u0027T LOVE MUSIC?  (Flamethrower in the\u003cbr\u003e\u0026#34;Flame ON\u0026#34; position!)  FUCK YOU!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWhat does it take, a $65,000 triode tube amp w/ comparable speakers to\u003cbr\u003e\u0027listen\u0027 to music?  What do you think \u0027listening\u0027 is?  I can be sitting ina noisy restaurant w/ quiet muzak \u0026 still know what song\u0027s playing, eventhough my wife can\u0027t even hear the music.  Is that \u0027listening\u0027???  It\u0027s\u003cbr\u003ecertainly ambient.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWhat I love about sound is that the essential quality comes thru whetheryou\u0027re playing it on a shitty VW mono speaker w/ a negative S/N ratio or ahigh-end.   Ongaku amp.  If you can\u0027t hear THAT w/o expensive hifi gear Isuggest that YOU\u0027RE THE ONE THAT\u0027S NOT \u0027LISTENING\u0027.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e808OUT, in no mood for elitist bastards...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYes, I know this is supposed to be a chill ambient virtual space.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eNow on Sony: Lady Burning Sky - N9000.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
  "amb_1994_10_188":  {
                          "subject":  "fwd - VCR Tapes/Headphones",
                          "from":  "Andrew Thomas \u003cathomas@hydra.acs.uci.edu\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Sun, 16 Oct 94 19:24:59 -0700",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e------- Forwarded Message\u003cbr\u003eDate: Sun, 16 Oct 1994 18:43:34 -0700 (PDT)\u003cbr\u003eFrom: Interstellar Groovy Dave \u003ccamde933@goshawk.csrv.uidaho.edu\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSubject: VCR Tapes\u003cbr\u003eTo: ambient@hyperreal.com\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e[Stuff about VCR Recording Eaten by /dev/null]\u003cbr\u003e\u003e of course it\u0027s all pretty silly in this day and age when you can buy a \u003cbr\u003e\u003e score of different digital formats on which to record your sounds...and\u003cbr\u003e\u003e the packages tend to be smaller.\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\tWell, for those of us without the cash to buy digital:  $300 or \u003cbr\u003eso for a DAT, or more, plus $8 to $10 per tape, it\u0027s much more \u003cbr\u003eeconomical, as well as portable, to use VCR tapes.  Assuming of course, that one already has a VCR.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\tVCR\u0027s, if the cables aren\u0027t totally poor, have excellent \u003cbr\u003erecording ability, according to the chief engineer here at KUOI.  So, I\u0027m willing to take him at his word, as he\u0027s pretty knowledgeable.  Of \u003cbr\u003ecourse, I\u0027d much rather make a DAT master, but since I\u0027m a poor college student, that\u0027s not feasible financially.  So, VCR tapes look to be an \u003cbr\u003eacceptable alternative.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\t\t\tGroovy Dave\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDate: Sun, 16 Oct 1994 18:50:54 -0700 (PDT)\u003cbr\u003eFrom: Interstellar Groovy Dave \u003ccamde933@goshawk.csrv.uidaho.edu\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSubject: Headphones\u003cbr\u003eTo: Mad Gil \u003ccyberpun@wam.umd.edu\u003e\u003cbr\u003eCc: ambient@hyperreal.com\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003e What\u0027s everyone\u0027s opinions on headphones?\u003cbr\u003e\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\tI love them when I want to catch more of the musical nuance than \u003cbr\u003ea regular speaker can deliver.  Mostly because I don\u0027t have any \u003cbr\u003eacoustically perfect listening spaces that I can use, so a decent pair of headphones (Sony $12 headphones work for me) I am able to get the full \u003cbr\u003e20-20K Hz range of the music.  Sure, the bass isn\u0027t ear-shattering, but that\u0027s okay, I\u0027d rather hear the pitch of it, than be hurt by it. 8-)  \u003cbr\u003eExcept when I\u0027m dancing of course.  Heheheh, but then I wear earplugs.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\tAnyway, a decent pair of headphones is nice, especially when I \u003cbr\u003ewalk to class, it lets me drift into my own worlds, and I only have to \u003cbr\u003ecome out when I take off the headphones.  Sort of a pain to carry a \u003cbr\u003espeaker stack around to class.  8-P\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\t\tGroovy Dave\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e------- End of Forwarded Message\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
