  "amb_1994_10_271":  {
                          "subject":  "REVIEW: Sharp+Laswell \"Visitation\"",
                          "from":  "\"Kent Williams\" \u003ccadsi.com!kent@elvis.cadsi.com\u003e",
                          "dateString":  "Wed, 19 Oct 1994 10:19:02 -0500",
                          "content":  "\u003cbr\u003eThis is the second duet disc on subharmonic that I\u0027ve bought, the first\u003cbr\u003ebeing \u0026#34;Psychonavigation,\u0026#34; the Namlook duet. The two records are extremelysimilar in approach, but not in content.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eI will warn people right now.  If you think open-ended synth jams with dubbass drifting in and out occasionally is boring, this record will bore you.I for one rather like the form.  These are very loose, exploratory pieces.\u003cbr\u003eJonas Sharp is, of course, Space Time Continuum.  While his STC records mightbe described as having a West Coast vibe, the work on Visitation is verydark.   He does what he does best on this record, which is to build up layersof sounds that subtly interact.  Compared to this record, though, his recent\u0026#34;Sea Biscuit\u0026#34; long player is downright poppy.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe first cut \u0026#34;Zurvan Akarana\u0026#34; has beats, but not much in the way of\u003cbr\u003erecognizable drum tracks.  Sharp sets up a reverb unit so that the repeatsfall on the beat, and then plays around the implied beat in the echo.  WhenLaswell kicks in, he does his usual thing.  I\u0027ve not quite decided what\u003cbr\u003eto  think of Laswell\u0027s playing -- either there\u0027s nothing to it, or he\u0027s amaster at understatement.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe second cut \u0026#34;Aion\u0026#34; is beatless, and is almost entirely Sharp.  When thebass kicks in, it\u0027s a loose pulse, almost ... subharmonic?  There\u0027s someLigeti style place-weights on tone clusters business.  About 19 minutes\u003cbr\u003ein some hissy percussion kicks in but it seems disconnected from the musicalparts.  This is an odd sort of ambience.  If you give it your full attention,you won\u0027t be bored; the constant shifts in texture will hold your attention.If you use it as sonic wallpaper, it will creep you out.  This is not blissmusic.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eSo what\u0027s my verdict?  I give it thumbs up, primarily because it\u0027s an extendedouting  for Mr. Sharp at his most experimental. Laswell\u0027s part of it seemspretty minimal -- maybe he was in charge of cuing the tape machine and rollingjoints.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e-- \u003cbr\u003eKent Williams -- kent@gilligan.cadsi.com\u003cbr\u003eLook in the mail header for all sorts of  vital information about me.\u003cbr\u003eI\u0027m continually AMAZED at th\u0027breathtaking effects of WIND EROSION!!\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"
                      },
